(20, 'from-the-bronze-ages-to-nowadays', 'From the Bronze Ages to nowadays', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'From the Bronze Ages to nowadays', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '\r\n\r\n                <div class=\"template-5\">\r\n                                    <div class=\"container\">\r\n                                        <div class=\"row\">\r\n                                            <div class=\"col-sm-12\" contenteditable=\"false\">\r\n                                                <h2><br></h2>\r\n                                            </div>\r\n                                            <div class=\"col-md-6 col-sm-12\" contenteditable=\"false\">\r\n                                                <p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align:justify\"><span lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif;\r\nmso-ansi-language:EN-US\">Artsakh is located in the highlands southeast of the\r\nLesser Caucasus, on the extreme eastern part of the Great Hayk. In the west it\r\nborders the eastern shore of Lake Sevan, to the southwest - the river Aghavno (Hagar)/,\r\nin the south - the river Yeraskh  (Araks),\r\nin the east deeps into the Mugan steppe, and in the north rare protected with the\r\nKarabakh ridge. Archaeological materials, Armenian and foreign sources evidence\r\nthat the human in Artsakh permanently lived from the ancient times. Here you\r\ncan find the ruins and traces of settlements, castles, buildings, various\r\nweapons, jewelry, tools found in the deep layers of the ground. Of particular\r\ninterest are materials found in the Paleolithic cave Azokh in Hadrout region,\r\nthe remains of a prehistoric human (Neanderthal). Today archaeologists of\r\nEngland and Spain, together with Armenian archeologists conduct excavations\r\nhere and discover new traces of life and activity of the ancient man.<o:p></o:p></span></p>\r\n                                            </div>\r\n                                            <div class=\"col-md-6 col-sm-12\" contenteditable=\"false\">\r\n                                                <p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align:justify\"><span lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif;\r\nmso-ansi-language:EN-US\">Artsakh mountains are rich in various monuments, petroglyphs\r\nare especially prevalent here. Their chronology is extensive and, starting from\r\nthe 7th century BC reaches 1st millennium.  Karvatchar region and the neighborhood of the\r\nvillage Tagհut of Hadrout region are particularly rich in petroglyphs.Bronze\r\nAge </span><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif\">Е</span><span lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif;\r\nmso-ansi-language:EN-US\">astern Armenian provinces were inherent in the\r\nconstruction of cyclopean fortresses. In Kashatagh region, on the left bank of\r\nthe river Hochants, it remained one of the fortresses. The first state\r\nformations on Armenian Plateau appeared in the 3-1 millennium BC. </span><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif\">А</span><span lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif;\r\nmso-ansi-language:EN-US\"> special place and the role was given to Van or\r\nUrartu, or Ararat Kingdom. During the reign of Argishti the 1st Artsakh was </span><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif\">а</span><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif;\r\nmso-ansi-language:EN-US\"> <span lang=\"EN-US\">part of Urartu, as evidenced by the\r\nchronicle of Argishti the 1st, found in Kotayk. The Chronicle also mentions the\r\ncity of Zar. The name of the city coincides with the medieval Artsakh melikate Zar\r\nand contemporary village Tsar of Karvatchar region.<o:p></o:p></span></span></p>\r\n                                            </div>\r\n                                        </div>\r\n                                        <div class=\"img-100p\">\r\n                                            <div class=\"img-block\">\r\n                                                <img data-toggle=\"modal\" data-target=\"#myModal\" data-title=\"Feedback\" src=\"http://storage.loc/web/img/about/d1d9a5e5-872d-4e02-866b-eea6098cf6fb.jpg\" alt=\"Gandzasar\" title=\"Gandzasar\">\r\n                                            </div>\r\n                                        </div>\r\n                                    </div>\r\n                                </div><div class=\"template-4\">\r\n                                    <div class=\"container\">\r\n                                        <div class=\"row\">\r\n                                            <div class=\"col-md-12 col-sm-12\">\r\n                                                <p contenteditable=\"false\"><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align:justify\"><span lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif;\r\nmso-ansi-language:EN-US\">Tigranes the Great built four cities in the primordial\r\nArmenia and named on his honor - Tigranakert. One of the cities was founded in\r\nArtsakh at the foot of Vankasar mount.Through the efforts of the Armenian\r\narchaeologists in 2006 deep under the ground were discovered the remains of ancient\r\nstructures of Artsakhian Tigranakert, which over and over again is a proof to “blind\r\nand deaf” opponents of the Armenian people that since the times of Noah, this\r\nland was inhabited by Armenians and imbued with the Armenian spirit.In Rome,\r\nyou can find a map of the world preserved from the time of Nero, carved on a\r\nmarble wall. Artsakh is marked on it as one of the provinces of the Armenian\r\nstate. This fact is documented by Greek and Roman chroniclers of the 5th\r\ncentury BC -1st century.<o:p></o:p></span></p></p>\r\n                                            </div>\r\n                                        </div>\r\n                                    </div>\r\n                                </div><div class=\"template-5\">\r\n                                    <div class=\"container\">\r\n                                        <div class=\"row\">\r\n                                            <div class=\"col-sm-12\" contenteditable=\"false\">\r\n                                                <h2><br></h2>\r\n                                            </div>\r\n                                            <div class=\"col-md-6 col-sm-12\" contenteditable=\"false\">\r\n                                                <p><span lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt;line-height:\r\n115%;font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif;mso-fareast-font-family:\"Times New Roman\";\r\nmso-ansi-language:EN-US;mso-fareast-language:RU;mso-bidi-language:AR-SA\">King\r\nVachagan sought to establish the unshakable foundations of the state and\r\nenhance the spiritual life of the country, as said Movses Kaghankatvatsi. He\r\nbuilt as many churches as days in the year and showed earnest efforts to\r\ndisseminate education.In the 9th century, the kingdom of Khachen was formed in\r\nthe western and northern regions of Artsakh. The power of this kingdom\r\nstrengthened the most in the end of the century, during the reign of Gregory\r\nAranshahik. In various provinces of Khachen, Aranshakhiks built impregnable fortresses\r\n- Khachenaberd, Levonaberd, Jraberd, delightful stone crosses-khachkars and\r\nmonastic complexes.Since the mid of 11th century, the prosperous life of the\r\nArtsakh principality was broken by invasions of Seljuk Turks. On the lands of\r\nthe Greeks and the Armenians the Turks established their own state, spreading\r\nevil and cruelty in the surrounding countries. Even under these conditions,\r\nbeing forced to settle in the mountains, the Armenian nation has preserved its\r\nancestral.</span><br></p>\r\n                                            </div>\r\n                                            <div class=\"col-md-6 col-sm-12\" contenteditable=\"false\">\r\n                                                <p><span lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt;line-height:\r\n115%;font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif;mso-fareast-font-family:\"Times New Roman\";\r\nmso-ansi-language:EN-US;mso-fareast-language:RU;mso-bidi-language:AR-SA\">Since\r\nthe beginning of the 16-th century up to the 30-s of the 17-th century, Armenia\r\nbecame the scene of wars to Safavid Iran and Ottoman Turkey, aspiring to\r\npolitical leadership in the West Asia.The independent Artsakh meliks confident\r\nin the inaccessibility of their fortresses, created a military alliance, which\r\nis known to history as Skhnakh. Armenian state of Artsakh was reborn. The main\r\nforces of Skhnakh army were concentrated in the provinces of Gyulistan and\r\nJraberd and at the foot of Mrav. It is also known as the Big Skhnakh, whose\r\nleader and inspirer was Gandzasar Catholicos Esai Hasan-Jalalyan. The province\r\nconsisting of five principalities, with the center in the settlement of Togh,\r\nled Dizakian Melik Egan, has been recognized as an independent state. Melik\r\nYegan using its warm relations with Nadir cared for the problems of Armenians\r\nin Eastern Armenia.In 1747, the Persian Shah was assassinated. The country\r\nbegan a period of anarchy. Taking advantage of the situation, the nomadic\r\nTurkic tribes, wandering in the area between the Kura-Araks, rallied around Panah,\r\nthe head of Sarudzhalil clan of Javanshir tribe. They settled in Tigranakert\r\nfortress in northeastern Artsakh, which in those days was called Shahbulag and\r\nfrom there attacked the princedoms of Khachen and Jraberd.</span><br></p>\r\n                                            </div>\r\n                                        </div>\r\n                                        <div class=\"img-100p\">\r\n                                            <div class=\"img-block\">\r\n                                                <img data-toggle=\"modal\" data-target=\"#myModal\" data-title=\"Feedback\" src=\"http://storage.loc/web/img/about/d1d9a5e5-872d-4e02-866b-eea6098cf6fb.jpg\" alt=\"Gandzasar\" title=\"Gandzasar\">\r\n                                            </div>\r\n                                        </div>\r\n                                    </div>\r\n                                </div><div class=\"template-4\">\r\n                                    <div class=\"container\">\r\n                                        <div class=\"row\">\r\n                                            <div class=\"col-md-12 col-sm-12\">\r\n                                                <p contenteditable=\"false\"><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align:justify\"><span lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif;\r\nmso-ansi-language:EN-US\">The contradictions in the Russian-Persian relations\r\nsoon escalated into war of 1804-1813 and 1826-1828 years. Artsakh meliks many\r\ntimes have put the military and material resources to ensure the victory of\r\nRussian arms, expecting to gain independence of the country.With the\r\nwholehearted participation of the Armenians, military victory of Russian army\r\nwas completed by the signing of Gulistan agreement on October 12-th, 1828, and\r\nTurkmenchay agreement on February 10-th, 1828.In accordance with the Gulistan\r\nТreaty, Karabakh, with the status of a separate national entity, passed under\r\nthe control of Russia. With the transition of Eastern Armenia, including\r\nArtsakh, to Russia, the Armenian people would not get the desired independence.\r\nPersian yoke was replaced by Russian. Despite their inputs, meliks were\r\ndeprived of their possessions, and even their own rights. Tatar khans and\r\nlords, to be obsequious with Russian rulers, became the masters of Armenian\r\nvillages and meliks’ estates.On May 12-th, 1920 the Soviet government of\r\nAzerbaijan with the support of the 11th Russian Red Army Sovietized Karabakh.\r\nAgain, the question of the so-called disputed territories arose in the arena.\r\nThe Bolsheviks involved in the process of the world revolution, to flatter their\r\nnew ally, Turkey, on July 5th, 1921 by the decision of the Caucasian Bureau of\r\nthe Bolshevik Russian Committee, handed over Nagorno-Karabakh to Azerbaijan.For\r\nthe final separation of Nagorno Karabakh from Armenia in 1923, it was\r\nestablished Nagorno-Karabakh Autonomous Region. Thus, Artsakh was separated\r\nfrom his native Armenia.At the end of the 80s the people of Artsakh once again\r\nwere forced to stand on the armed defense of their homes.In May and June of\r\n1991, the Azerbaijani special armed units (OMON), together with the Soviet\r\nArmy, conducted an operation \"Ring\". Accompanied by military\r\nhelicopters, battle tanks and armored vehicles, they attacked and destroyed the\r\nArmenian settlements of Getashen and Shahumyan regions.The next step to eradicate\r\nthe Armenians of Artsakh and take possession of the historical territories was\r\nthe extermination of the Armenians of Nagorno-Karabakh Autonomous Region. In\r\nJune 1991, more than 20 Armenian villages of Martakert and Hadrout regions were\r\ncompletely destroyed; hundreds of women, children and elderly were killed and\r\nwounded. More than 700 people were captured, who had been tortured in\r\nAzerbaijani prisons. Thousands of people were forced to leave their ancestral\r\nhomeland.On September 2-nd, 1991 in Stepanakert, a joint meeting of the Councils\r\nof People\'s Deputies of the Nagorno-Karabakh region and the Shahumyan district\r\nadopted the Declaration of Independence of the Republic of Nagorno-Karabakh.Schools\r\nand cultural centers began to revive out of the ruins. It was necessary to\r\nsolve the day-to-day problems of thousands of displaced people from Azerbaijan.\r\nAll this was impossible without the participation of Armenia, without moral,\r\npolitical and material support of the Armenians all over the world. Hundreds of\r\nkilometers of roads, dozens of school buildings, cultural centers were built\r\nwith the support of the Diaspora.<o:p></o:p></span></p></p>\r\n                                            </div>\r\n                                        </div>\r\n                                    </div>\r\n                                </div>', '\r\n\r\n                <div class=\"template-5\">\r\n                                    <div class=\"container\">\r\n                                        <div class=\"row\">\r\n                                            <div class=\"col-sm-12\" contenteditable=\"false\">\r\n                                                <h2><br></h2>\r\n                                            </div>\r\n                                            <div class=\"col-md-6 col-sm-12\" contenteditable=\"false\">\r\n                                                <p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align:justify\"><span lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif;\r\nmso-ansi-language:EN-US\">Artsakh is located in the highlands southeast of the\r\nLesser Caucasus, on the extreme eastern part of the Great Hayk. In the west it\r\nborders the eastern shore of Lake Sevan, to the southwest - the river Aghavno (Hagar)/,\r\nin the south - the river Yeraskh  (Araks),\r\nin the east deeps into the Mugan steppe, and in the north rare protected with the\r\nKarabakh ridge. Archaeological materials, Armenian and foreign sources evidence\r\nthat the human in Artsakh permanently lived from the ancient times. Here you\r\ncan find the ruins and traces of settlements, castles, buildings, various\r\nweapons, jewelry, tools found in the deep layers of the ground. Of particular\r\ninterest are materials found in the Paleolithic cav